Lists — ordered, indexed, and they allow duplicates.

A list is ordered, indexed, and allows duplicates. The two implementations you will meet ninety nine percent of the time are array list and linked list. Array list is backed by a resizing array. Random access by index is constant time. Append at the end is amortised constant time, because the array doubles when it fills. Insertion or removal in the middle is linear time, because every element after the insertion point has to shift. Array list is your default choice. Linked list is a doubly linked list. Insertion and removal at either end is constant time. Random access is linear time because you have to walk the chain. Linked list is rarely the right choice in modern Java. For queue and stack workloads, use array deque instead, which is faster than linked list at every operation.

The list interface gives you the operations you would expect. The add method appends to the end. The get method takes an index and returns the element. The indexOf method searches for the first occurrence. The contains method checks membership. The set method replaces an element at an index. The remove method by index removes at that position and shifts. The remove method by value removes the first occurrence.
